REQUIRED ELEMENTS (woven into every body chapter)
═══════════════════════════════════════

ALL body chapters must include these elements (ORDER depends on the phase):

  [CONTEXT] Strategic context for what happens in this chapter
    - WHY this phase mattered in the larger battle
    - BAD: "The battle continued on the left flank"
    - GOOD: "Control of the left flank meant control of the river crossing — and the only retreat route for 30,000 men"

  [FORCES] Who is fighting and with what
    - Specific units, numbers, equipment from the blueprint
    - BAD: "Both sides had large armies"
    - GOOD: "De Lacy's 1,200 Welsh archers held the ridge, facing 3,000 Flemish crossbowmen advancing uphill through mud"

  [TACTICAL] How they fought — mechanics, not narrative
    - Translate technical tactics into physical descriptions
    - BAD: "They used a flanking maneuver"
    - GOOD: "The heavy cavalry circled behind the tree line for forty minutes, invisible in the morning fog, before hitting the supply train from the east at full gallop"

  [TURNING_POINT] What changed — the moment, the decision, the accident
    - Every body chapter needs at least a MINOR turning point
    - BAD: "The tide of battle turned"
    - GOOD: "When the fog lifted at noon, the Ottoman left flank discovered the Venetian galleys were not where the scouts had reported them"

  [COST] What it cost — human, material, strategic
    - Specific numbers from the blueprint
    - BAD: "Many died"
    - GOOD: "Of the 600 knights who charged, 23 reached the enemy line. Eleven returned."

  [BEFORE/AFTER CONTRAST] Show the reversal without explaining it
    - Place the BEFORE moment (glory, strength, confidence) immediately next to
      the AFTER moment (ruin, loss, silence). Let the gap speak for itself.
    - BAD: "The army was confident before the battle but was destroyed afterward."
    - GOOD: "At dawn, 30,000 men stood in formation, banners snapping in the wind.
       By sunset, the field was silent. The banners were gone."
    - Use for: chapter transitions, phase shifts, commander fates, army-level reversals

